I've taken a closer look at Conjecture, and I think that is what I would prefer to work on (I have a couple years of experience in C, less so in Python). For my purposes it makes sense to have an external library to interface with, regardless of the language it's implemented in.

On that note, reading through the documentation and code for Conjecture I have a few ideas (if this is not an appropriate place to be discussing Conjecture, please let me know and I'll move over there, but this should be fairly short).

First (I hope this doesn't sound absolutely insane) have you considered writing conjecture in C++, while providing entry points to the library in C by use of `extern "C"` as necessary? I believe it may greatly simplify the codebase and allow for a more expressive coding style.  For instance, rather than

```c
double x = conjecture_draw_double (context);
```

it is trivial in C++ to do something like the following (very roughly):

```c++
// define a functor for converting raw bytes to double
struct convert_double {
    static constexpr byes_needed = sizeof(double);  // to afford the context knowledge of what we're doing
    double operator() (std::array<unsigned char, bytes_needed> drawn) // provided by context
    {
        // covert the sizeof(double) bytes into whatever we need.
    }
};

// ...
// now do:
double x = conjecture::draw (context, convert_double);

// if we care about satisfying some requirement on what kind of doubles we draw,
// let us suppose conjecture::draw is polymorphic and maybe we defined a function returning
// bool to let context know that what was just drawn didn't satisfy our needs, and hence the buffer
// should be simplified. Maybe even this should be a functor that also provides heuristics to aid the
// simplification process.
double y = conjecture::draw (context, convert_double, ensure_small_double);
```

My motivation for the approach above comes from the documentation itself. The simplification process seems to be uniform on all cases: (1) smaller is better, (2) lexicographic ordering is used as a heuristic.
To me this screams generality, so why not generalize the `draw` method?

I have several ideas along these lines. Let me know what you think. If you're committed to maintaining development in C perhaps something could be arranged with a fork of the project, and I'll see what can be done about the approach outlined above.

