@drjova Yes, you can just do it in a custom serialiser. I think the main point here is that most people will need it, so would be nice with a reusable solution.

You can't use ``url_for`` to generate the URL for the records-ui for very good reasons. It think the best is simply to inject into records rest the right pattern for generating html links. Something along the lines of: 

```python
RECORDS_REST_ENDPOINTS = dict(
    records=dict(
        links_factory=default_link_factory('/records/{pid.pid_vaule}'),
    )
)
```

@msolima your fix worked for me as well. However when I wanted to add `UserAttributeSimilarityValidator` into the mix I realised that the fix was not that simple. It is because `UserAttributeSimilariryValidator` requires the User instance to be passed in. This does not happen currently since djoser uses serializer field validation which does not have access to user instance.

I like @pik's idea of re-using the `AUTH_PASSWORD_VALIDATORS ` settings in djoser considering DRY principles. Some digging into Django [documentation](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.11/topics/auth/passwords/#integrating-validation) suggests us to use `validate_password` if we are writing our own mechanisms to change password which is exactly whats being done here.

Considering this I think we can implement password validation in djoser something like below and remove populating password validators in djoser settings again.


```
class PasswordResetConfirmView(utils.ActionViewMixin, generics.GenericAPIView):
   ...
    def _action(self, serializer):
        validate_password(serializers.data['new_password'], serializer.user)
        serializer.user.set_password(serializer.data['new_password'])
        serializer.user.save()
        return Response(status=status.HTTP_204_NO_CONTENT)
```

